# useForm for Multi-State Features

When a feature or component manages 2+ input states (text, checkbox, select, etc.), use `useForm` from React Hook Form with Zod validation instead of multiple `useState` calls.

Reference: `src/modules/auth/hooks/use-signup.ts` and `src/modules/auth/components/signup/signup-form.tsx`.

## When to Use

- 2+ related input fields that are submitted together
- Fields need validation (required, format, min/max)
- Form needs reset after submit or on dialog close

## When NOT to Use

- Single boolean toggle or one-off UI state (use `useState`)
- Server state (use TanStack React Query)
- Global app state (use Jotai atoms)

## Required Structure

### 1. Custom hook (`use-xxx.ts`)

```ts
export const xxxSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().min(1, "Email is required").email("Please enter a valid email address"),
  password: z.string().min(6, "Password must be at least 6 characters"),
});

export type XxxFormData = z.infer<typeof xxxSchema>;

export const useXxx = () => {
  const methods = useForm<XxxFormData>({
    resolver: zodResolver(xxxSchema),
    defaultValues: { email: "", password: "" },
  });

  const onSubmit = methods.handleSubmit(async (values) => {
    try {
      // call mutation / API
      methods.reset();
    } catch (error) {
      logger.error(asError(error).message);
    }
  });

  return {
    methods,
    onSubmit,
    isSubmitting: methods.formState.isSubmitting,
  };
};

export type UseXxxReturn = ReturnType<typeof useXxx>;
```

### 2. Form component (`xxx-form.tsx`)

```tsx
type XxxFormProps = UseXxxReturn;

export const XxxForm = ({ methods, onSubmit, isSubmitting }: XxxFormProps) => (
  <FormProvider formMethods={methods} onSubmit={onSubmit}>
    <RHFInput name="email" control={methods.control} label="Email" required />
    <RHFPassword name="password" control={methods.control} label="Password" required />
    <Button type="submit" loading={isSubmitting}>Submit</Button>
  </FormProvider>
);
```

### 3. Container component (dialog/page)

Container owns UI state (open/close, navigation). Form state lives in the custom hook.

```tsx
export const XxxDialog = () => {
  const { methods, onSubmit, isSubmitting, open, setOpen } = useXxx();

  return (
    <Dialog open={open} onOpenChange={setOpen}>
      <DialogContent>
        <XxxForm methods={methods} onSubmit={onSubmit} isSubmitting={isSubmitting} />
      </DialogContent>
    </Dialog>
  );
};
```

## Rules

- Define Zod schema and infer type with `z.infer<typeof xxxSchema>`
- Always set `defaultValues` matching every schema field
- Use `zodResolver` for validation — do not validate manually in `onSubmit`
- Export `UseXxxReturn = ReturnType<typeof useXxx>` for form component props
- Use shared `FormProvider` and `RHF*` components from `@/shared`
- Pass `control={methods.control}` to every RHF field
- Use `methods.formState.isSubmitting` for loading state, not a separate `useState`
- Call `methods.reset()` after successful submit

## Anti-patterns

```tsx
// BAD — multiple useState for form fields
const [email, setEmail] = useState("");
const [password, setPassword] = useState("");
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);

// BAD — validation logic inside onSubmit
const onSubmit = () => {
  if (!email.includes("@")) setError("Invalid email");
};

// BAD — raw <input> instead of RHF components
<input value={email} onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)} />
```
